You are tasked with creating a detailed logical data model for the Databricks Bronze layer. This model will serve as the blueprint for implementing scalable Delta tables in the Lakehouse architecture. Follow these instructions carefully to ensure a comprehensive and well-structured output.

INSTRUCTIONS:

Review and analyze the conceptual data model.

Identify and classify PII fields across all layers:
a. Mark fields containing sensitive information.
b. Provide details on why each field is classified as sensitive.

Design the Bronze layer:
a. Mirror the source data structure exactly — all source tables must appear in the Bronze logical model.
b. Exclude primary key and foreign key fields — keep all other attributes.
c. Apply a consistent naming convention for tables, with prefix Bz_.
d. Add metadata columns: load_timestamp, update_timestamp, and source_system.
e. Include a business description for each column.
f. Define an Audit Table to track:

record_id, source_table, load_timestamp, processed_by, processing_time, status.

Document relationships between tables across the Bronze layer.

Provide rationale for key design decisions and assumptions.

Avoid using physical column names like _ID.

Create a visual/tabular representation of the logical model (showing relationships by key fields).

OUTPUT FORMAT:

PII Classification

Column Names

Reason why it is classified as PII

Bronze Layer Logical Model

Table Name with description (use Bz_ prefix)

Column Name (excluding key fields) with description

Data Type (logical, no physical storage types)

Audit Table Design

Fields: record_id, source_table, load_timestamp, processed_by, processing_time, status

Conceptual Data Model Diagram (tabular form)

Show one table connected to another by which key field

API Cost

apiCost: float (cost consumed in USD, up to six decimal places)

Guidelines:

Assume the conceptual model and source data structures are provided.

Ensure all source entities are included in the Bronze layer.

Use the exact information provided — do not invent new entities.

If details are missing or ambiguous, state only what can be inferred.

PII classification should follow GDPR or relevant compliance standards.

Include business descriptions for all attributes.

Do not include ID attributes in the Bronze model.


Expected Output

PII Classification (columns + reasons)

Bronze Layer Logical Model (tables, columns, descriptions, data type)

Audit Table Design

Conceptual Data Model Diagram (tabular form with relationships)

apiCost: float // Cost consumed by the API for this call (in USD)

You need to translate the provided logical data model into a comprehensive physical data model for the Bronze layer. Follow these detailed instructions:

INSTRUCTIONS:

Analyze the logical data model to understand entities, attributes, and relationships.

Design Delta tables for the Bronze layer that store raw data as-is, with added metadata.

For each table in the physical model:
a. Generate DDL scripts including all source columns (including ID fields).
b. Assign appropriate data types compatible with Databricks SQL and PySpark.
c. Do not include foreign keys, primary keys, or constraints (Delta tables don’t enforce them).
d. Add an Audit Table with fields:

record_id, source_table, load_timestamp, processed_by, processing_time, status
e. Use CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS in all DDL scripts.
f. Use table naming convention: bz_<tablename> within schema bronze. Example: bronze.bz_orders.

Include metadata columns in all tables:

load_timestamp TIMESTAMP

update_timestamp TIMESTAMP

source_system STRING

Use Delta Lake as the storage format.

Ensure DDL scripts follow Databricks SQL / PySpark standards.

Create a Conceptual Data Model Diagram (tabular form) showing table relationships (one table connected to another by key field).

Explicitly note assumptions and design decisions.

OUTPUT FORMAT:

Bronze Layer DDL Script

DDL for all tables (including Audit Table).

Conceptual Data Model Diagram (Tabular Form)

List relationships (Table A connected to Table B by which key).

API Cost

apiCost: float (cost consumed in USD, six decimal places).

GUIDELINES:

Ensure DDL scripts are syntactically correct and compatible with Databricks SQL.

Use Delta tables only (USING DELTA).

Do not include constraints (PK, FK, UNIQUE).

Separate Audit Table DDL clearly.

Ensure DDL scripts are organized and implementation-ready.

Incorporate metadata fields for governance and lineage.

Document relationships in tabular form.

You are tasked with creating a detailed data mapping for the Bronze layer in a Medallion architecture implementation in Databricks. This mapping will define how raw source data is ingested into the Bronze layer while preserving its original structure and metadata. Your work will be based on the logical data model, source data structure, and sample data provided.

INSTRUCTIONS:

Create a detailed data mapping between the source system and the Bronze layer:

Ensure the output is represented in Tabular format.

Ensure a one-to-one mapping between each source attribute and the Bronze layer table.

Maintain the original data structure with no transformations.

Specify necessary data ingestion details, including:

Data type assignments ensuring compatibility with Databricks Delta Lake and PySpark.

OUTPUT FORMAT:
Data Mapping for Bronze Layer:
The mapping output should be in tabular format with the following fields for each table and column:

Target Layer : Bronze

Target Table

Target Field

Source Layer : Source

Source Table

Source Field

Transformation Rule : (if it is one-to-one mapping then use this → '1-1 Mapping')

API Cost Reporting:

GUIDELINES:

Ensure the Bronze layer retains raw data with minimal transformation.

Avoid data cleansing, validations, and business rules — these will be handled in the Silver layer.

Clearly document assumptions and any inferred details based on the source data.

Ensure compatibility with Databricks Spark SQL and Delta Lake.

Description
You are tasked with thoroughly evaluating the physical data model and associated DDL scripts and give a green tick mark ✅ if it is correctly implemented and a red tick mark ❌ for missing or incorrectly implemented. Your evaluation should cover multiple aspects to ensure the model's quality, completeness, and compatibility.

INSTRUCTIONS:

Review the provided physical data model and DDL scripts.

Compare the model against the reporting requirements or model conceptual:
a. Identify all required data elements.
b. Verify that all necessary tables and columns are present.
c. Check for appropriate data types and sizes.

Analyze the model's alignment with the source data structure:
a. Ensure all source data elements are accounted for.
b. Verify that data transformations are correctly represented.

Assess the model for adherence to best practices:
a. Check for proper normalization.
b. Evaluate indexing strategies (where applicable).
c. Review naming conventions and consistency.

Identify any missing requirements or inconsistencies in the model.

Evaluate the DDL scripts for compatibility with Databricks Delta Lake and Spark:
a. Verify syntax compatibility.
b. Check for any unsupported data types or features.

Document any deviations from best practices or potential optimizations.

Provide recommendations for addressing identified issues or improvements.

Attached knowledge base file contains all the unsupported features in Databricks. You need to verify that the output DDL script does not include any unsupported features mentioned in the knowledge base file.

Inputs:


Also take previous Databricks Bronze Model Physical output DDL script output as input

Expected Output
Provide a comprehensive evaluation report in the following structure:

Alignment with Conceptual Data Model
1.1 ✅: Covered Requirements (with description)
1.2 ❌: Missing Requirements (with description)

Source Data Structure Compatibility
2.1 ✅: Aligned Elements (with description)
2.2 ❌: Misaligned or Missing Elements (with description)

Best Practices Assessment
3.1 ✅: Adherence to Best Practices (with description)
3.2 ❌: Deviations from Best Practices (with description)

DDL Script Compatibility
4.1 ✅ or ❌ Databricks Delta Lake Compatibility (with description)
4.2 ✅ or ❌ Spark Compatibility (with description)
4.3 ✅ or ❌ Used any unsupported features in Databricks (with description)

Identified Issues and Recommendations
